properties.flavorText: This malfunctioning guardian must have wandered away from Norkos, and is now trapped in Cabran.
Swing at anything that gets in your way. Fairly large, you might need an extra arm to use it effectively.
A pointed red hat worn by the denizens of the Gnomish Village. Always in season!
A holy relic of Ganomulus, The God of Garden Gnomes and Lost Laundry. Whenever you look away, it strikes a different pose.
In Gnome society, the Gnome with the most fanciful beard is appointed lord.
This ogre is missing both legs, and replaced them with tree trunks.
A gnome sized shovel used to maintain the prestine gnomish gardens.
Accidently left by Mountain Town resident Timmy during one of his adventures.
The remains of a guard who perished in the ogre attacks.
Trophy tusks gathered by the Ogre Lord. Each tusk comes from an ogre who challenged his authority.
A divine gift granting the holder atonement with the deities of Idliathlia.
How did you find my secret cave?
A tattered cloak bearing the insignia of Mountain Town.
Lead the successful raid on the upper level of Mountain Town, forcing the residents below.
Has the body of a human, but the head of a snake. Challenges all those who dare enter the Temple of the Snake.
Planted in the earth halfway up the mountain path. It seems whoever brought the flag decided not to continue their journey.
The grave of a former resident of Desert Town.
Here lies Cruril Tarmikos the Wise.
What even is this color anyway?
A case study on Cleric's teachings. By sacrificing the self, Cleric learned to renew the life of others.
A valuable resource from the center of Desert Town.
Used by Druid in a ritual to cleanse the Swamp Tower of evil.
A reclusive mage. Her touch has the ability to turn flesh to lead or gold, depending on her mood. One of the Dreadlords of Cabran.
One of Fencer's prized fighting swords.
A beautiful landscape of the jungle south-west of the nearby cliffs. Who would have left this behind?
An imperfect transmutation stone that can change the properties of non-magical objects. The Transmuter was still working on perfecting this mythical stone.
Down in the jungle, you're likely to die.
A small stick that fell from the absurdly large tree housing Tree Town.
A popular grain amongst the giants. The taste is terrible, but it grows well even in poor soil.
A half-giant-half-ogre monster, chained to the nearby pillars to act as a guard for Lord Ironfist.
A large magical horn overflowing with fresh foods. A single pour could provide a feast for a hungry adventurer.
Tossed down by Fencer before initiating combat.
Useful for throwing in the eyes of your enemies for a surprise attack.
An enormous living gold statue protecting the entrance to the Gilded Mushroom Forest. The elements bend to the statue's will.
Waiting for favorable conditions to spawn a new Gilded Mushroom.
An aged wooden sign warning adventurers to turn away from the Mountain of Mayhem.
A sophisticated looking set of glasses that were brought to Idliathlia by Bitomancer.
A star shaped badge similar to the ones carried by the Norkian Wardens. How did this get way out here?
A slice of petrified wood from one of the large trees in Lamega Forest.
A carefully carved statue depicting the giant Lord Ironfist. The sculpture depicts Lord Ironfist with a foot on another giant's head and crushing the skull.
Floating at sea for years. The message is asking for help from a nearby island.
Lost at sea for some time.
Mage is quite the fishing enthusiast.
Stranded here for years, the lost adventurer has started a primitive life on this island.
Crudely crafted from scavenged supplies.
Is this swamp water, or something else? Eww...

A decorative piece of artwork that doubles as a protective cover for Beatomancer's mystical music.
A unique species of insect prized by Druid. No one is sure how such a small creature is capable of flight with wings of stone.
Used to cut down the large trees of Lamega Forest.
The woods near Tree Town are known for their remarkable quality, which is part of the reason the Shackles guards try to gather as much of it as they can.
Hastily written down by a Shackles guard during a bout of drunken debauchery.
Rogue would call this one of the many 'tools of the trade.'
One of the Trickster's lost cards. Despite any original meaning, Trickster likes to stick this card to people he does not care for.
Used to safely contain maps or other documents. Everything inside is blank, though.
Expertly cut by an unknown individual.
A beautiful piece of art, and the only surviving animal from Clockborg's menagerie.
Priceless because it is one of a kind, or priceless because the attached tag is blank?
I was hoping for a gold one.

A trinket from Necromancer's forgotten past.
Just the right size to use as a walking stick.
This ugly diva used to live in the other Swamp Tower, before it sank into the sea.
No tiny umbrella, what a shame.
Covered in small gems. Quite large for a hand mirror and in the shape of a beetle.
In perfect condition, which is remarkable for a flute sitting in a cave for so long.
Interested in a lifetime of mining? Inquire within.

A gnome-sized portal that leads to a nearby beach. You can probably squeeze through here though.
